```python
class Queue:
    def __init__(self):
        self.in_stack = []
        self.out_stack = []

    def enqueue(self, item):
        self.in_stack.append(item)

    def dequeue(self):
        if self.out_stack == []:
            while self.in_stack != []:
                self.out_stack.append(self.in_stack.pop())
        return self.out_stack.pop()
```

In this implementation, the Queue class uses two stacks - one for enqueuing items (self.in_stack) and one for dequeuing items (self.out_stack). When an item is added to the queue (enqueue method), it is added to the in_stack. When an item is removed from the queue (dequeue method), it is removed from the out_stack. If the out_stack is empty, the in_stack is reversed and added to the out_stack so that items can be dequeued in the correct order.
